{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_brookland_ver01/data/sn84026749/00205696404/1930120301/0271.xml":{"full_text":"Financial Market News, Stocks, Bonds, Commodities and Comment\nMs RISE\nISDUEIN\nMARKET\nSecurities Advisor Believes\nTrend Will Point Upward If\nStocks Are Steady Now\nBy THE SPECTATOR\nThe market wiggled a lit\ntle higher yesterday, and\nShowed a strong front to\nmilted news from the busi\nness world, as divided omis\nsions and a sharp decline in\nmail order sales. Firmer\ncopper prices and rumors of\nsteel price stabilization helped\ncounteract this. If the mar\nket can continue to show\nthe same backbone for a\nweek or two longer, it will\nbe definitely bullish. In the\nmeantime wait and see.\nI\u2014 \u2014I\n5 Steel Shows Up\nSteel common was one of the\nstrong spots in yesterday\u2019s mar\nket on rumors that higher steel\nprices for the first quarter would\nbe announced in the next day or\ntwo. Since many producers have\nalready announced prices for the\nfirst quarter. The report be\ncomes questionable. Probability\nis that some action on stabiliza\ntion of prices is nearer the truth.\nThis has been in the air for some\ntime, and an announcement to\nthis effect now would more than\nmake up for any further decline\nin production the rest of the\nmonth. Buying of steel yesterday\ncame from well-informed quarters,\nbut I wouldn\u2019t chase the stock up\non the present advance.\nElectric Power and Light made\nan excellent showing for the year,\nreporting $2.93 a share against\n$2.79 last year. At current levels\nthe stock is selling at slightly\nmore than 15 times earnings\nwhich isn\u2019t so bad when you con\nsider Electric Power\u2019s big stake in\nthe natural gas industry through\ncontrol of United Gas Corpora\ntion. I advise waiting for a re\naction before buying it, however.\nCopper Brightens\nThe copper situation is turning\na little brighter. The red metal\nis back at 11 Vi cents a pound,\nand interests in the know look\nfor it to sell at 12 cents a\npound the price at which it was\npledged following the agreement\non world-wide copper curtailment,\nbefore many days are passed.\nThis development would send the\ncopper stocks higher, and their\naction yesterday suggests that\nthey can be bought for a turn.\nHowever, don\u2019t follow the coppers\non a bulge. I want to see three\nthings before I turn bullish on\nthem. First, good-sized, steady\nsales; second, real curtailment in\nproduction, and third, decline in\nsurplus'stocks. Earnings will take\ncare of themselves in this case\nas far as the leaders like Kenne\ncott and Smelting are concerned.\nI see no reason for bothering\nwith the others at this time.\nWarner Brothers, I understand,\nearned slightly more than $1 a\nshare in the first quarter of its\nfiscal year, which ended Novem\nber 30. Profits, are running at a\nrate which promises better than\n$3 a share for the years it is said.\nMovie attendance currently is\noff 10 per cent from a year ago.\nI am told, but the film shares at\ncurrent levels seem to have dis\ncounted this.\nMail Order Sales\nAnnouncement that Montgom\nery Ward sales for November\nwere 24.9 per cent below the\nsame month last year makes the\nrecent move in the stock look\nodd, especially since the com\npany ran at a big loss in the\nfirst nine months of the year.\nEarnings at present are running\nin the black, according to Presi\ndent Strawn, but the company\nhas' a long way to go to break\neven for year. It seems unlikely\nthat sales of Montgomery Ward\nor Any of the other mail order\nhouses will show any decided up\nturn for\u2019 a few months. In view\nof this, I believe there is plenty\nof time to buy the stock with a\ngood chance of getting it lower.\nDividend cut by Mack Trucks\nto a $4 basis removes the uncer\ntainty hanging over the stock,\nand I look for it to work gradu\nally- higher. Mack will come\nr 1 \u25a0mi\nW. B. HIBBS CO.\nThe ONLY New York Stqck Exchange House\nHaving Its Main Office in Washington\nMEMBERS\nNew York Stock Exchange\nBoston Stock Exchange\nPhiladelphia Stock Exchange\nWashington Stock Exchange\nNew York Cotton Exchange\nChicago Board of Trade\n1 American Bankers Association\nDistrict Bankers Association\nHIBBS BUILDING\nNational 0540 WASHINGTON, D. C.\nBank Mentor\n*r~\n\u2014Times staff Photo\nJOHN W. POLE\nCOMPTROLLER OF CUR\nRENCY, who in his review of\nbanking conditions throughout\nthe country declared that the\nAmerican Banking situation is\nsound and that the future of\nthe banks throughout the coun\ntry would be steady.\nGAG MAINS IN\n0. G. JAN. I\nPatrons of the Washington\nGas Light Company will be\nfurnished with natural gas by\nthe first of the year, according\nto announcement made today at\nthe offices of the utility.\nThe 20-inch mains have how\nbeen laid to within three miles\nof Rockville, the installation crews\ncontinuing to make excellent\ndaily showings.\nNatural gas which is to be\nconsumed locally will be brought\nfrom the fields of eastern\nKentucky and West Virginia, 500\nmiles away. The branch main\nto. Rockville, however, is being\nbrought from Coatesville, Pa., a\ndistance of 100 miles.\nEngineers in charge of the\nrouting and laying of the big\nmains have overcome stupendous\nobstacles in bringing the pipes\nacross mountain ranges and\nrivers. Each section of pipe is\nwelded, as it is laid, the whole\nforming a continuous unbroken\nconnection with field to focal\ndistributing plants.\nCash Is Available\nFor Argentine Bonds\nWith $207,836 in cash avail\nable for the purchase of Gov\nernment of the Argentine Na\ntion external sinking fund 6\nper cent gold bonds of 1924,\nseries B, due December 1, 1958,\nthe Chase National Bank of New\nYork invites tenders of such\nbonds.\u2019 at a flat price below par.\nTenders with coupons due on\nand after June 1, 1931, should\nbe delivered at the trust depart\nment Os the bank, 11 Broad St.,\nbefore 3 p. m., December 11.\nIf tenders so accepted are not\nsufficient to exhaust the moneys\navailable, additional purchases by\ntender, below par, may be made\nup to February 28, 1931.\npretty close to earning its new\ndividend this year, and it has\nplenty of cash. The company\nwill benefit from any improve\nment in general business.\nConsolidation\nFailure of the Eastern rail\nroad men to get together on\nconsolidation is another thorn in\nthe side for the much battered\ncarriers. What with the severe\nshrinkage in earnings and in\ncreasing competition the rails\nseem to be getting more than\ntheir share of trouble.\nCelanes Corporation, unknown\nto the average trader, seems\nheaded for a record. Yesterday\u2019s\nadvance of 3 points brings it\nwithin 2% points of its high for\nthe year. If It can break through\nit will\u2019 deserve some kind of a\nrecord, what with the rest of the\nlist hanging near its lows.\nTHE WASHINGTON TIMES\nRAIL MERGER!\nPARLEYENDSIN\nDEADLOCK\nPeace Conference Between\nHuge Railroad Organizations\nEnds in Definite Break\nThe Eastern railroad executives\u2019\n\u201cpeace\u201d conference to divide the\nsystems east of the Mississippi\ninto four trunk lines and end\ntheir battle of millions has\nbroken up, The Washington Times\nlearned today.\nOne of the larger systems has\nrefused to continue negotiations\nand the conference has been in\ndefinitely postponed. This comes\nright on the heels of widely cir\nculated reports in the last few\ndays that an agreement had been\nreached and would be submitted\nto the Interstate Commerce Com\nmission for approval.\nThe I. C. C. about two years\nago attempted to solve the East\nern railroad fight and drew up a\ntentative plan dividing the East\nern roads into five trunk lines.\nThe five systems were to be the\nBaltimore and Ohio, Chesapeake\nand Ohio, Pennsylvania, New\nYork Central and Wabash. The\nChesapeake is the Van Sweringen\nbrothers of Cleveland system.\nAtterbury Blamed\nThe Wabash, now controlled by\nthe Pennsy, was the fifth trunk\nline. Its creation is being fought\nby the Van Sweringens and the\nB. O. with some help from the\nNew York Central. The Pennsyl\nvania, bitter foe of the Van Swer\ningen and the B. 0., has been\nin sympathy with the plan.\nThe Pennsylvania is understood\nto be the road that refused to\ncarry the negotiations for a four\nline trunk plan any further.\nGen. William Wallace Atterbury,\nthe Pennsy\u2019s aggressive president,\nis the individual blamed most\nfor the break up of the confer\nence. One Eastern executive is\nreported to have said:\n\u201cAs long as Atterbury is head\nof the Pennsylvania there will\nnever be any agreement on a\nfour trunk Hne.\u201d\nPennsy Holding\nIn proposing the creation of a\nfifth trunk line around the\nWabash, the I. C. C. urged combi\nnation of the Wabash, Lehigh\nValley, Pittsburgh West Vir\nginia, Wheeling Lake Erie, Sea\nboard Air Line, the old Ford line,\nDetroit, Toledo Ironton and\nthe Western Maryland. The\nWabash, Lehigh and Pittsburgh\nWest Virginia are controlled\nby the Pennsylvania or interests\naffiliated with it. These same\ninterests have a large stock hold\nings of Seaboard.\nThe Western Maryland is con\ntrolled by the B. 0., which has\nrefused to relinquish its hold. The\nWheeling Lake Erie is con\ntrolled by the Van Sweringens\nand they want to add the Pitts\nburgh West Virginia. The New\nYork Central would like either\nthe Delaware, Lackawanna\nWestern or the Lehigh. Interests\nfriendly to the Central virtually\ncontrol the Lackawanna.\nIn addition .to its stake on the\nEastern systems, the Pennsy, its\nbankers and affiliates are about\nthe largest stockholders in the\nNew England roads.\nLONG ISLAND R. R.\u2014Net\noperating income for 10 months\nended October 31, amounted to\n$7,188,800, compared with $8,146,-\n785 in corresponding 1929 period.\nOctober net operating income\nwas $729,067, against $716,383 in\nOctober, 1929.\nRECOVERY\n\nTHE readjustment of stock prices which\nhas taken place over the past year\nhas been more or less without discrim\nination. We believe the recovery from\nlow levels will be to a great extent\nselective rather than general\nMembers Jn vJew c ha n ged conditions, every\nBaltimore investor should analyze hjs investments.\nSTOCK EXCHANGES We wj g a J fQ su m ft re p o rfj on\nAssociate Member the position and prospects of any se-\nNEW YORK CURB .7\nexchange cunhesyou may hold.\nMackubin, Goodrich Co.\nESTABLISHED 1899\nBANKERS\n1508 H STREET REDWOOD SOUTH STS.\nWASHINGTON. 0. C BALTIMORE. MD.\nGeneral Trade Conditions\nShow Improvement\nBy LEWIS HANEY\nDirector New York University Bureau\nof Businens Research and Former\nEconomist of Federal Trade\nCommission\nFrankly and without any arti\nficial optimism, let us examine\nthe more favorable side of the\nbusiness situation. There is a\ngood deal to be thankful for in\nthe real facts.\nIn the first place, the credit\nsituation as a whole is by no\nmeans bad. This is very differ\nent from conditions in such de\npressions as occurred in 1893 and\n1907. The Federal Reserve Sys\ntem is strong, with its gold re\nserve large and increasing, and\nthe reserve ratio up to 81.4 per\ncent (against 71.8 per cent a\nyear ago). It now has able\nleadership.\nMembers Improve\nThe condition of the member\nbanks, while not perfect, is im\nproved. Their liability on ac\ncount of stock market loans has\nbeen greatly reduced. Brokers\u2019\nloans are low. Even total col\nlateral loans are now being re\nduced. The member banks are\nborrowing at the reserve less\nthan one quarter as much as a\nyear ago. Direct bank loans on\nsecurities are still pretty large,\nand total loans and investments\nare more than 9 per cent above\ntotal deposits, but these condi\ntions are being corrected.\nThe numerous failures of West\nern banks and some of the forced\n\u201cmergers\u201d may be considered as\nweeding out the weak ones and\nestablishing a stronger position.\nThe general soundness of bank\ncredit has some bearing on com\nmodity prices. These seem to be\napproaching stability in so far as\nthe basic raw materials are con\ncerned. It is really quite notable\nthat few, if any, such commodi\nties are making new lows. While\nsome articles, mostly manufac\ntures, still seem out of line, such\nthings as cotton, copper, rubber,\nsugar, silk, zinc, wheat and corn,\nseem to have hit bottom.\nIt can be said, too, that con\nsiderable progress has been made\nMack Trucks Div.\nCut to $4 Basis\nMack Trucks, Inc., directors to\nday cut the dividend on the com\nmon stock by declaring a quar\nterly payment of $1 a share on\nthe issue, placing it on a $4 an\nnual basis, against the $6 previ\nously paid since the beginning of\n1928. The dividend is payable\nDecember 31 to holders of record\nDecember 15.\nThe company reported for the\nnine months ended September 30,\nnet earnings equivalent to $3.09\na share against $7.85 a share in\nthe like 1929 period.\nCity Ice Dividend\nTo Be Continued\nThe City Ice Fuel Co. in a\nletter sent to stockholders today\nstated that in view of the satis\nfactory current earnings it is ex\npected that the customary quar\nterly dividend of 90 cents a share\nwill be continued in 1931. It was\nalso stated that the earnings for\nthe year ended December 31 will\nabout equal the $4.69 a share\nearned last year.\nWilson Co. Makes\nBack Payment\nWilson Co. directors today\ndeclared a dividend of $1.75 a\nshare on account of the accumu\nlations on the 7 per cent cumula\ntive preferred stock, payable Jan\nuary 2 to holders of record De\ncember 12. The accumulations\namount to $7 a share.\nTA\u00ab National Daily\nin readjusting the prices of fin\nished commodities and even re\ntail prices.\nSharp Recessions Over\nThe next point that impresses\nme is that we have probably\npassed through the panic stage\nof the cycle and have seen the\nlast of the very sharp recession.\nJudging by the past, we may\nnow expect dullness and irregu\nlarity. Business is not going to\nstart upward soon (or if it should,\nit would suffer another setback).\nBut if we will let prices and pro\nduction alone, stabilization will\nsoon develop and that be followed\nin due course by recovery.\nOn the one hand, Industrial\nproduction has now been cut to\nabout 25 per cent below \"normal.\u201d\nMercantile inventories are very\nmoderate. On the other hand,\nconsumers are gradually using up\nclothing, buildings, automobiles,\netc. And at the same time, sav\nings are accumulating, so that\nwhen consumers must buy again,\nmany will have the means. (In\ncidentally, we note that many\nmillions are being released from\nChristmas savings funds). All\nthese things are quietly working\nto bring business revival.\nMany Favorable Factor*\nFinally, a number of favorable\nsymptoms can be pointed out.\nDepartment stores have held up\nwell. Cotton textile manufactur\ning has shown improvement.\nWholesale dry goods sales gained\nin October. Orders for new\nfreight cars have been placed by\nthe railways in good volume.\nStructural steel awards continue\nfair, and some sections report\nimprovement in residential build\ning. The early bringing out of\nnew models by one or two auto\nmobile manufacturers indicates\nhopefulness and has brought some\ngat>s in employment and steel\ndemand.\nBusiness is not nearly as bad\nas it could be, and I am hopeful\nthat by spring everyone will be\nlooking ahead to the coming good\ntimes.\nBANKERS PAPER\nINTERESTS\nThe monthly bulletin of the\nDistrict of Columbia Bankers* As\nsociation, issued today, contains\na number of articles of excep\ntional interest to Washington\nbankers.\nAn article by Edward J. Mc-\nQuade, first vice president of the\nLiberty National Bank and first\nvice president of the District As\nsociation, analyzes provisions of\nthe new estate law recently\nenacted in New York.\nMcQuade suggests that many\nof the provisions of the new regu\nlations might well be put into ef\nfect in Washington and suggests\nthat the matter be taken up with\nthe judges of the District Su\npreme Court and Bar Association\nwith a view to meeting present\nconditions and removing many re\nstrictions now existing with refer\nence to distribution of small es\ntates.\nBankers Council\nMeeting Announced\nThe monthly meeting of the\nCouncil of Administration of the\nDistrict of Columbia Bankers\u2019\nAssociation is to be held at 4 p. m.\nFriday, December 5. This session\nwas originally scheduled to be\nheld last Friday, according to\nPresident Lanier P. McLachlen.\nWEDNESDAY\u2014DECEMBER 3\u20141930\nBUDD DECLARES\nNORTHERN INILL\nHOLD ITS MEN\nNo Further Reductions Con\ntemplated, President As\nsures St. Paul Newspaper\nST. PAUL, Minn., Dec. 3.\n\"The Great Northern railway\ndoes not expect to make any\nfurther reductions in forces\nhere this winter, or, generally\nspeaking, anywhere along its\nsystem.\u201d\nRalph Budd, president, stated\nthis today in answer to a query\nfrom the Pioneer-Press-Dispatch,\nwhich is conducting a survey of\nlocal payrolls.\nMaintenance Up\nThe railway will continue to\nkeep its property in the highest\nstate of maintenance, Mr. Budd\nsaid. There are about 25,000 em\nployes at the present time; the\nnumber employed in St. Paul is\n3,500.\nThe policy adopted several\nyears ago of doing car and loco\nmotive work in the railway\u2019s\nshops during the winter to pro\nvide maximum employment for\nshop employes will be continued\nthis winter, Mr. Budd announced.\nDuring the last five-year period,\nthe Great Northern railway had\nexpended a total of nearly $15,-\n000,000 for shop work, and up to\nSeptember 30 this year, the\nGreat Northern\u2019s expenditures for\nequipment built in company shops\nwas $2,000,000.\nROCK ISLAND HELPS\nCHICAGO, Dec. 3.\u2014Shops of\nRock Island lines which were re\nopened on November 17, will re\nmain open during the first two\nweeks of December, thereby giv\ning continued employment to\nabout 2,100 shopmen during that\nperiod. The, management hopes\nto operate shops at least four\nweeks out of every six during the\nwinter.\nI\nWarner Company\nExpanding Plants\nWarner Company has appro\npriated approximately $900,000 for\nnew plant construction and expan\nsion, Charles Warner, president of\nthe company has announced.\nThese funds will be expended in\nthe establishment of additional re\ntail terminals for distribution of\n\u201cCentral-Mix\u201d concrete and to en\nlarge the facilities of terminals\nnow in operation.\nUse of centrally mixed concrete\nin building construction has shown\nrapid growth in the past 18\nmonths, according to Warner.\nYT7ZXYATA WOULD YOU LIKE TO GET A CHECK\nSgt Ha Im// UM THIS FOl YOU* m\nS flvJ TT NEXT CHRISTMAS?\nSR An Baay WagrTo Oct M ASmWayToHmM N*\n8 E3SSIEQ3B'3jMKjQ33SSSI B\na\nS\nnsg y V*X i JHn\nvEg tSSpr jtS\nw\nffw oa \u00aea\ni I\nggc h I* Easy Money! jffl|\n|||x ALL YOU HAVE TO DO IS TO BECOME A MEMBER OF\ng Our Christmas Club\nS& in any one of the banks listed below\ngfefc American Security and Trust Co. Mt. Vernon Savings Bank\nEg, Anacostia Bank Munsey Trust Company g\nSsE Bank of Brightwood National Bank of Washington\nBank of Commerce Savings Water Street Branch only hK&\ntigk Chevy Chase Savings Bank' National Savings Trust Co.\nSsf, Columbia National Bank North Capitol Savings Bank Igg\nOfc Commercial National Bank r>ark Savings Bank JO\nffi Departmental Bank Potomac Savings Bank\nDistrict National Bank Riggs National Bank gg\nEast Washington Savings Bank Second National Bank\nB Federal-American National Bank Security Savings Com. Bank\nTrust Co. Union Trust Company\nFranklin National Bank Washington Loan Trust Co.\nLincoln National Bank Washington Mechanics Sav. Bank gg\nMcLachlen Banking Corporation Washington Savings Bank SI\nS& MEMBERS, DISTRICT OF COLUMBIA BANKERS ASSOCIATION g\nWall Street\nHtears\nThat holders of Consolidated\nGas (G) have been switching\ninto other stocks.\nThat U. 8. Pipe and Foundry\n(CJ) is receiving considerable\nattention from the professionals.\nThat the November result*\nwill determine fate of Canada\nDry (DGL) $5 dividend.\nELECTRIC FIRM\nSHOWS LOSS\nEASTERN TEXAS ELECTRIC\n\u2014Net operating revenue for Oc\ntober amounted to $301,522,\nagainst $333,039 in October, 1929.\nTwelve months ended October 31\nshowed a surplus after charges\nof $2,107,429, compared with $2,-\n191,863 in corresponding 1929\nperiod.\nCOLONIAL BEACON OIL CO.\n\u2014Nine months ended September\n30 showed a net loss of $1,576,-\n360, after depreciation and inter\nest, against a profit, before Fed\neral taxes, of $869,386 in similar\n1929 period. September quarter\nshowed a net loss of $260,196,\ncontrasted with a profit, Before\nFederal taxes, of $338,877 in like\n1929 quarter.\nCARRERAS, LTD.\u2014Year ended\nOctober 31 shows a net profit,\nafter all charges, of \u00a3968,204,\nagainst \u00a31,285,154 in correspond\ning 1929 period.\nDELAWARE HUDSON R. R.\nCORP.\u2014Quarter ended Septem\nber 30, net income was $1,071,-\n937, after taxes and charges,\nagainst $135,477 in preceding\nquarter.\nJORDAN MOTOR CAR CO.\u2014\nNine months ended September 30\nshowed a net loss of $667,083,\nafter charges, contrasted with a\nprofit of $133,041, before Federal\ntaxes in like 1929 period. Sep\ntember quarter showed a net loss\nof $231,712, against net loss of\n$18,097 in similar 1929 quarter.\nPuget Sound Power\nApproves Increase\nBOSTON, Dec. 3.\u2014Stockholders\nof Puget Sound Power and Light\nCompany, have voted to increase\nthe authorized common shares to\n2,000,000 and the authorized pre\nferred shares to 500,000.\nIn addition, directors of the\ncompany havp offered rights to\ncommon stockholders for the pur\nchase of additional new common\nstock at $25 per share in the\nratio of 5 new shares for each\n8 held.\nBANK SITUATION\nCALLED GOOD\nBT POLE\nComptroller of Currency Sees\nProgress Looming Ahead\nand Situation Clearing Up\nThe general banking situation\nof the nation is good although\nmany banks in \u201cover banked\u201d\nsmall towns, are having an uphiU\nfight, John W. Pole, comptroller\nof the currency, testified before\nthe House Appropriations Com\nmittee, it was revealed in hear\nings made public today,\nPole said:\nThe general banking situation\nhas not greatly changed since\nlast year. The Metropolitan\nBank situation is not any prob\nlem, speaking generally, but the\ncountry banks are. having a\nrather uphill time in some in\nstances.\n\u201cThe agricultural conditions\nand the limited possibilities\nthat they have for making\nmoney have restricted their op\nportunities a good deal. The\ncity banks are not making as\nmuoh money as they made last\nyear, but we have no apprehen\nsion on that score.\u201d\nPole said the effect of big\nbanking mergers have been, in\nthe main very good.\nHe said 443 national banks\nwere in receivership on October\n31, as compared to 426 a year\nago. During the year 104 banks\nclosed,\nReal Estate\nLoans\n(D. C. Property Only)\n6%\nNo Commission Charged\nYou can take 12 years to pay off\nyour loan without the expense of\nrenewing. >I.OOO for >l4 per\nmonth including interest and\nprincipal. Larger or smaller\nloans at proportionate rates.\nPERPETUAL\nBUILDING\nASSOCIATION\nEstablished 1881\nLargest in Washington\nAssets Over $23,000,000\nCor. Uth and E N. W.\nJAMES BEBBV. President\nEDWARD C. BALTZ. Secretary\n27","height":"30178","width":"24217"}}
